1‚êüTHE FALSE LIGHT‚êüThe self-magnifier‚êüIn the dim time before the true sun and moon had risen, a great plumed being, Wuqub Kak'ix, exalts himself. His eyes shine like polished metal, his teeth are gleaming jewels, his face is bright with the light of gemstones. He proclaims himself to be both the sun and the moon, the light and the path of all the people.‚êüBefore the true light has come, the loudest claimant rushes to fill the empty seat. The age of dim half-light always produces a being who declares himself the sun ‚Äî radiant only by reflection, jeweled, magnified ‚Äî and demands to be taken as the light and the way. Vainglory is not a true light; it is borrowed glitter mistaken for the dawn.‚êû2‚êüTHE FALSE LIGHT‚êüThe offense to the Heart of Sky‚êüHis claim is false: he is not the sun, his glow neither ripens the maize nor orders the days. The Heart of Sky is not pleased that a vain pretender has set himself up in the sky before the real dawn. The twin boys Junajpu and Ixb'alamkej resolve to bring him down.‚êüThe test of a light is whether things grow by it. False radiance ripens nothing and orders nothing; it only dazzles. What heaven will not abide is not brightness but the counterfeit that occupies the place of the true and so keeps the real dawn from breaking.‚êû3‚êüTHE SHOOTING‚êüThe nance tree‚êüEach day Wuqub Kak'ix climbs his great nance tree to eat its yellow fruit. The twins watch and learn his habit, and lie in wait beneath the leaves with the blowgun.‚êüEven the self-declared sun must come down to eat. Every false greatness has a tree it returns to, a hunger that fixes its routine and exposes it. Patience and close attention find the hour that pride cannot skip.‚êû4‚êüTHE SHOOTING‚êüThe blowgun strikes the jaw‚êüJunajpu fires; the pellet strikes Wuqub Kak'ix square in the jaw. He crashes down from the tree, his gleaming mouth ruined and howling ‚Äî but he is not killed.‚êüThe first true blow lands on the mouth ‚Äî on the boastful jaw, the organ of the false proclamation. But unmasking is not undoing; wounded vanity grows more dangerous, not less. The bright teeth are broken; the being itself is not yet brought down.‚êû5‚êüTHE SHOOTING‚êüThe torn-off arm‚êüJunajpu lunges to seize him, but Wuqub Kak'ix grips the boy's arm and wrenches it from his body. He carries the arm home and hangs it over his hearth-fire to smoke, swearing the boys will pay.‚êüConfront false power too directly, too soon, and it tears a piece of you away. It will hang what it took over its fire as trophy and warning. The wound is real; the arm is gone. From here the work must become cunning, not force.‚êû6‚êüTHE HEALERS‚êüThe two white elders‚êüThe twins go to two wise old ones ‚Äî Saqi Nim Aq and Saqi Nima Tz'iis, white-haired grandparents ‚Äî and ask their help. The boys will travel as their grandchildren, and the elders will present themselves as humble healers who cure the eyes and teeth.‚êüForce having failed and cost an arm, the twins borrow age and humility. They return not as warriors but as the grandchildren of unassuming healers. Disguise as the lowly is the road back in: power will open its mouth to a humble doctor that it would never open to a rival.‚êû7‚êüTHE HEALERS‚êüThe summons of the vain‚êüWuqub Kak'ix lies in agony ‚Äî his jaw throbs, his jewel-teeth are cracked, his eyes ache. Hearing of healers who mend teeth and eyes, he summons them at once, desperate to have his ruined radiance restored.‚êüThe false sun's undoing begins in his own craving to be beautiful again. Vanity wounded will invite the very hands that will finish it, so long as they promise to bring back the shine.‚êû8‚êüTHE HEALERS‚êüJewels traded for maize‚êüThe healers tell him the only cure is to draw the broken teeth and set new ones. They pull out his gemstone teeth and replace them with teeth of white maize; they strip the shining metal and jewels from around his eyes. As the glitter leaves him, so does his greatness.‚êüThis is the dismantling substitution ‚Äî the mirror image of IxK'ik's resin heart. There, craft set a made thing in the place of the true to PRESERVE a life; here, craft sets humble maize in the place of jewels to STRIP a falsehood. The same nawal art of replacement unmakes counterfeit radiance: trade the gemstone for the grain, and the false sun simply goes out. What looked like glory was only the jewels; take them away and nothing divine remains.‚êû9‚êüTHE HEALERS‚êüThe going-out, and the arm restored‚êüStripped of his shining teeth and jeweled eyes, Wuqub Kak'ix loses his brilliance and his power, and he dies. The twins take Junajpu's arm down from the hearth and set it back in place, and he is whole again.‚êüCounterfeit light need not be slain in battle; it need only be un-adorned. Once the borrowed glitter is gone, it expires of its own emptiness. And what the false power tore from you is recoverable ‚Äî the arm comes back off the fire and is made whole ‚Äî once the falsehood that seized it is gone.‚êû10‚êüTHE ELDER SON‚êüSipakna, who claims to make the mountains‚êüWuqub Kak'ix's elder son, Sipakna, boasts that he himself makes the mountains, raising them up in a single night. He is vast, strong, and proud.‚êüFalse greatness breeds heirs. The pride of the false sun passes to a son who claims to make the very mountains ‚Äî to be the author of the unmovable. Self-magnification, left standing, begets the claim to have founded the world itself.‚êû11‚êüTHE ELDER SON‚êüThe Four Hundred Boys become Motz‚êüThe Four Hundred Boys (Omuch' K'ajolab') try to bring Sipakna down: they have him help drag a great log, then dig a deep pit to bury him. He outwits them, hides in a side-tunnel, and when they drink to celebrate his supposed death, he topples their house upon them. The four hundred die ‚Äî and rise into the sky as Motz, the handful of stars.‚êüThe strongman lets the many dig the very pit meant for him, then buries them under their own roof while they toast his fall. But the four hundred are not erased: the crushed community rises as Motz, the fistful of stars by which planters still read the seasons. Those the strongman destroys become the guide-lights overhead ‚Äî the same field of stars the risen ones of the descent will one day join.‚êû12‚êüTHE ELDER SON‚êüThe false crab, and Sipakna turned to stone‚êüThe twins bring Sipakna down by his appetite. They fashion a lifelike crab from carved stone and bromeliad flowers and set it deep in a canyon beneath the mountain Meawan. Famished, Sipakna crawls in after it; the mountain comes down upon him and he is turned to stone.‚êüThe maker of mountains is undone by a made thing and his own hunger ‚Äî lured by a crafted bait beneath the very mountain he claimed to raise, and fixed there as stone. The one who called himself the author of the unmovable becomes a piece of it. Pride that names itself the foundation ends as inert rock.‚êû13‚êüTHE YOUNGER SON‚êüKab'rakan, who throws the mountains down‚êüThe other son, Kab'rakan, boasts the opposite power: he topples the mountains, shaking the earth and unmaking whatever stands.‚êüThe other face of false greatness is not building but breaking ‚Äî the boast of the one who can bring anything down, who mistakes destruction for power. Where the brother claimed to found the world, this one claims the right to shake it apart.‚êû14‚êüTHE YOUNGER SON‚êüThe earth-rubbed bird‚êüThe twins meet him, praise a distant great mountain to provoke his pride, and offer him a roasted bird ‚Äî but they have rubbed it with white earth. As he eats, his strength drains away; the earth in the bird unmakes his might. Weakened, he is bound and buried, and the shaking of the mountains is stilled.‚êüThe breaker is fed the very earth he scorned, and it hollows out his strength from within. Offer arrogant force a feast seasoned with the humble ground it despised, and its power quietly leaves it. The earth itself takes back the one who claimed dominion over it.‚êû15‚êüTHE GROUND CLEARED‚êüBefore the dawn‚êüWith Wuqub Kak'ix and his two sons brought down, the false lights and the false foundations are cleared away. The world is made ready for the true sun, and for the people of maize who will one day rise to greet it.‚êüAll of this ‚Äî the false sun unmade, the false mountains stilled ‚Äî is preparation. The counterfeit must be cleared before the true dawn can be borne, for an age cannot receive its real light while a pretender still sits in the sun's seat. The un-making of the false is not the story's end but the clearing in which a true beginning becomes possible.‚êùreview‚êü{"attestor":{"name":"PENDING: named K'iche' attestor","role":"PENDING"},"basis":"K'iche' Maya ceremonial lineage","scope":"faithfulness of the transmission (script) layer to the Popol Wuj","date":"PENDING"}‚êü{"reviewer":{"name":"Dr. Vincent James Stanzione","role":"lineage accountability holder"},"status":"complete","date":"2026"}‚êühttps://labaluka.net